id: pm-tlpv
title: "SDK describeExtensionBlueprint: static author-time surface map of a composeExtension blueprint (author-time inverse of describeExtensionActivation)"
description: "Add `describeExtensionBlueprint(blueprint): ExtensionActivationSummary` to the SDK. It computes the exact same flat, sorted, de-duplicated named-surface summary that the runtime `describeExtensionActivation` (pm-16ue) returns, but PURELY from the declarative `ExtensionBlueprint` data — without loading, activating, or running any side effects.\n\nWhy: `composeExtension` (pm-iqq0) lets authors declare what to register as data, and `deriveExtensionCapabilities` already gives the author-time capability set without activation. But to see the full named surface map (commands, overrides, handlers, hooks, item types/fields, importers/exporters, search/vector adapters, parser/service/renderer overrides, flag targets, preflight count) an author still has to compose -> activate -> describe. This closes that asymmetry: capabilities have an author-time deriver; named surfaces now do too.\n\nFidelity: command paths are normalized with the SAME exported `normalizeCommandName` the loader uses, and importer/exporter handler paths are synthesized as `normalizeCommandName(\"<name> import|export\")`, exactly mirroring `toRegistrationCommandPath`. A keystone parity test asserts `describeExtensionBlueprint(bp)` deep-equals `describeExtensionActivation(activate(composeExtension(bp)))` for a blueprint exercising every surface, so any future drift in registration mechanics fails CI. The imperative `activate` escape-hatch is intentionally NOT reflected (a static describer cannot see arbitrary code) and this is documented.\n\nScope: src/sdk/compose.ts (co-located with composeExtension/deriveExtensionCapabilities), SDK barrel export, docs/SDK.md Declarative Authoring section, 100% test + docstring coverage."
type: Feature
status: closed
priority: 2
tags[3]: "area:extensions","area:sdk",pm-cli
